      },
      {
        "scenario": "D: Network partition to Stripe for 2 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: First 5 requests each block a worker for 10s (full timeout). At ~50s, circuit breaker opens. After that, Stripe calls fast-fail — this is good. Timeline: 0-50s: 5 threads consumed, throughput degraded ~25%. 50-110s: Circuit open, all Stripe calls fail fast (<1ms), fraud checks still execute (wasted work). 110s: Half-open, probe request sent, times out at 120s (partition still active), circuit reopens. Service recovers ~60s after partition heals (next half-open probe succeeds). BLAST RADIUS: 100% payment failure for 2 min + ~60s recovery tail = ~3 min total outage. SURVIVABILITY: Service survives thanks to circuit breaker. The 50s initial degradation window is the risk — under high load those 5 blocked threads can cause queuing. FIX: (1) Reduce Stripe timeout to 5s to cut the initial pain window in half. (2) Consider returning a 'payment pending' response during circuit-open state instead of hard failure. (3) Add circuit breaker state to metrics and alert on state=open."
